              <tr><td><strong>Transformation</strong></td><td>Before/after using the product</td><td>Beauty, fashion, fitness</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Duet / stitch</strong></td><td>Respond to a brand's seed video</td><td>Reactive campaigns, tutorials</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Product demo</strong></td><td>Show a creative use of the product</td><td>DTC gadgets, food, apps</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Storytelling / POV</strong></td><td>Share a personal story around a theme</td><td>Cause campaigns, service brands</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real branded hashtag challenge examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Chipotle #GuacDance — 430M video starts in 6 days</h3>
        <p>To promote National Avocado Day, Chipotle ran <code>#GuacDance</code>, tying a dance to the song "The Guacamole Song." Result: <strong>250,000 user-submitted videos</strong>, 430 million video starts, and a one-day sales record for guacamole. Cost-per-submission worked out to well under $1.</p>

        <h3>2. Fitness app #MoveWithMe — 15K videos, 80M views</h3>
        <p>A fitness app ran a 10-day challenge inviting users to demo their favourite workout move with a branded hashtag. Result: 15,000 user videos, 80 million aggregate views, and a 22% lift in app downloads over the baseline.</p>

        <h3>3. Food delivery #DinnerIn30 — 12% download lift</h3>
        <p>A food-delivery brand ran <code>#DinnerIn30</code>, asking users to show a meal they could plate in 30 minutes using the app. Result: 25,000 submissions, an aggregated hashtag page with 40M views, and a 12% app-install lift for the campaign window.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Branded hashtag challenge vs. regular branded hashtag</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Branded hashtag challenge (paid)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Paid Discover-page placement on TikTok</li>
              <li>Requires seed video + creator seeding</li>
              <li>6-day amplification window</li>
              <li>Costs $100K-$150K+ base package</li>
              <li>Designed to generate mass UGC in days</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4><a href="/glossary/branded-hashtag/">Branded hashtag</a> (organic)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Free — just create and use the tag</li>
              <li>No forced participation format</li>
              <li>Compounds over months to years</li>
              <li>No minimum spend</li>
              <li>Built for long-term social proof, not spikes</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 branded hashtag challenge best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Pick a challenge action a 10-year-old can do.</strong> Complexity kills participation. If it needs choreography or a script, most users bounce.</li>
          <li><strong>Seed with 5-10 diverse creators.</strong> Mix macro and micro tiers. Each demonstrates a different way to interpret the challenge.</li>
          <li><strong>Tie the challenge to a native TikTok sound.</strong> Sound-driven challenges consistently outperform silent ones.</li>
          <li><strong>Design for the algorithm's early signals.</strong> The first 24 hours' completion rate, likes, and shares set the ceiling for the whole campaign.</li>
          <li><strong>Give creators creative freedom.</strong> Brand-scripted seed videos underperform against "here's the vibe, do you" briefs.</li>
          <li><strong>Attach a business metric goal, not just views.</strong> App installs, promo-code redemptions, or branded-search lift — otherwise you buy vanity.</li>
          <li><strong>Re-share top submissions for 30 days after.</strong> Extending the tail keeps the tag alive well past the paid window.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — under-investing in seeding</div>
          <p>Brands often assume the paid placement alone will drive participation. It won't. Without <a href="/glossary/brand-deal/">brand deals</a> for 5-10 creators in the first 48 hours, most challenges die at 200 submissions and a wasted six-figure spend.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common branded hashtag challenge mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Making the challenge too complex.</strong> Multi-step, prop-heavy, or dance-heavy challenges lose casual participants.</li>
          <li><strong>Under-seeding.</strong> Under 5 creators seeding = under 5,000 submissions on average.</li>
          <li><strong>Overly branded seed videos.</strong> Ad-shaped seed videos signal "this is a commercial" and depress user participation.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring business metrics.</strong> Views and submissions are inputs. Downloads, sales, and branded-search are outcomes. Measure both.</li>
          <li><strong>Killing the momentum at day 7.</strong> The organic tail lasts 30-90 days if you keep re-sharing top posts and updating the brand feed.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps brands capture the search demand a challenge creates</h2>
        <p>A viral TikTok challenge produces a giant spike in branded searches over 48-72 hours. If your Google results, product pages, or comparison pages are not ready, you spend $150K driving traffic that lands on nothing. theStacc audits your <a href="/glossary/branded-keywords/">branded-keyword</a> coverage, closes the ranking gaps, and makes sure that when a Chipotle-sized moment hits your brand, the search engine ROI is captured — not wasted. Every challenge should have a search plan attached, not a hope.</p>

